image.altText: A skateboarder on the top of a brick wall.

props.synopsis: The city of Canberra may only be 112 years old, but it has many things worth preserving, like a brick skate park in the south, and pine trees and 1960s flats in the north. But there can be hurdles to recognising and preserving heritage as the city grows.

title.children: It accidentally became a skateboarding mecca. Now it's up for heritage listing

image.altText: A handgun with a label tied to it.

props.synopsis: The ACT Firearms Registry remains mostly paper based. Both police and the government say the "very analogue" system needs to go fully digital as soon as possible.

title.children: 'Loopholes and lags': The ACT's gun registry is still mostly paper based

image.altText: A woman walking into court with another woman.

props.synopsis: Canberra's only prison breached the human rights of a former Aboriginal detainee by illegally strip-searching her while she was held in remand there in 2021, the ACT Supreme Court has found.

title.children: Aboriginal woman's human rights breached by illegal strip search in jail

image.altText: Telstra Tower in Canberra from an aerial view.

props.synopsis: A budget deficit and proportionally high debt, along with rising health costs and major infrastructure projects, see ACT's credit rating downgraded to AA.

title.children: Budget deficit and high debt see ACT's credit rating downgraded to AA

image.altText: The exterior of a concrete building that reads "Law Courts of the Australian Capital Territory" over the entrance.

props.synopsis: A mother and son have been cleared of kidnap charges after they collected two of the woman's younger teenage sons as they walked to school and took them interstate, away from their father.

title.children: Mother and son cleared of kidnapping her two younger sons

image.altText: Hero postcard

props.synopsis: Georgia Curry bought a postcard from an op-shop after the cursive writing and old stamp caught her attention. It unlocked a 79-year-old mystery she is still getting to the bottom of.

title.children: A funky stamp led Georgia to buy an old postcard. She says it was fate

image.altText: Tina bends her knees and appears to sing or scream upwards, her fists clenched, in the black and white photograph.

props.synopsis: The new portrait comes in two parts — known as a diptych — and will be on display at the National Portrait Gallery from September 6 to mark Tina Arena's 50-year career.

title.children: Artist says Tina Arena became 'like a sister' while sitting for portrait

image.altText: Composite

props.synopsis: Your health is at stake as climate change impacts deepen, but it's not too late to do something about it, according to the new chair of the ACT Climate Council. And some Australians making hyperlocal changes are already reaping surprising benefits.

title.children: 'Hyperlocal' eco-choices leaving Australians healthier and better off

image.altText: Carlos Alcaraz clenches his fist

props.synopsis: The best two players on the men's tour face off in a third straight grand slam final as Jannik Sinner takes on Carlos Alcaraz in the US Open decider. Follow live.

title.children: Alcaraz wins US Open over Sinner, reclaims world number one ranking

image.altText: A man with a bandaged arm sits in front a tent across from a boy

props.synopsis: Hundreds of thousands of Palestinians are being told to immediately leave Gaza City, as the Israeli military's campaign to take over and occupy the area intensifies by the hour.

title.children: Palestinians in Gaza City consider evacuating for their children's sake

image.altText: A Ukrainian woman wearing a green top and jacket crying and standing in front of a bomb-destroyed smoking building

props.synopsis: Russia has attacked Kyiv with more than 800 drones in the largest aerial bombardment on Ukraine since the war between the two nations began, killing at least four people.

title.children: Kyiv hit by war's biggest drone attack as Trump threatens Russia with tariffs

image.altText: Anti-immigration rally Canberra

props.synopsis: Australia's Neo-Nazis sought to make their own message out of anti-immigration marches, and they succeeded.

title.children: Australia's Neo-Nazis have had an unadulterated propaganda win

image.altText: A woman standing in a warehouse with hi-vi jacket

props.synopsis: Cosmetics entrepreneurs through to tech developers say Austrade's signature export grant has become unfair, badly managed and opaque, all while many are struggling to adjust to Donald Trump's US tariffs.

title.children: Austrade outrage as exporters detail 'disaster' grants process

image.altText: Albanese and four other men walk down a hallway, the BCA logo visible on material behind them.

props.synopsis: Hinting at a debate on company profits tax, the prime minister will flag his government is looking at "fair and affordable" ways to incentivise investment at an annual address to big business.

title.children: PM flags corporate tax reform in speech to big business

image.altText: Four anonymous silhouettes in front of a court building which reads 'Family Court of Australia'.

props.synopsis: From lawyers "maximising fees" to a family report writer's warning that "your case is a murder-suicide waiting to happen", these parents share allegations of their experience in the Family Court of Australia.

title.children: 'Crushing': Parents desperate for changes to family law system

image.altText: Smiling Anthony Falconer in a grey T-shirt, bearded and wearing glasses, background is blurred.

props.synopsis: A local council has awarded nearly half a million dollars' worth of contracts to a builder with a fraught past.

title.children: Man behind multiple company collapses wins $400k council contract

image.altText: Lando Norris and Oscar Piastri shake hands, Italian Grand Prix pit lane

props.synopsis: Oscar Piastri has said he has no issues with McLaren calling team orders late in the Italian Grand Prix, allowing his teammate and championship rival to overtake him for second place.

title.children: Piastri hands second place to Norris after team orders called in Italy

image.altText: Mercury Psillakis takes a selfie of him and his brother who is holding a surfboard

props.synopsis: A childhood friend has described the "heroic" final act of a surfer who steered his friends to safety before being mauled by a shark at Sydney's Northern Beaches on Saturday.

title.children: Friend describes 'heroic' final act of Sydney surfer killed in shark attack

image.altText: A man in a suit and glasses looks up, with a microphone in front of him

props.synopsis: Japan's Prime Minister Shigeru Ishiba quits to avoid a split within the ruling Liberal Democratic Party.

title.children: Japan's PM resigns amid mounting pressure and a historic election defeat

image.altText: A larger portrait of a teenage boy sits before a crowd of Catholic clergy in white robes and pink skull caps.

props.synopsis: Carlo Acutis, an Italian teenager who died in 2006, becomes the first saint of the internet age.

title.children: First millennial saint canonised by Pope Leo at the Vatican

image.altText: a student walking on lego

props.synopsis: With an estimated one in five children experiencing chronic pain at some point in their lives, researchers are helping teachers respond to pain in the classroom with empathy.

title.children: Invisible, chronic pain common in kids and a challenge for teachers

image.altText: Woman with wide hat and red work shirt and jeans getting out of ute

props.synopsis: A regional Queensland doctor is urging drivers to slow down and drive more responsibly, saying road trauma should not be accepted as "part of doing business in this country".

title.children: Regional towns hurting as Qld road toll soars above 200 deaths

image.altText: Authorities patrol Dee Why Beach after a man was killed by a shark

props.synopsis: The NSW premier says the decision to put the brakes on the trial is "the right thing to do" after a shark claimed the life of surfer Mercury Psillakis.

title.children: Trial to remove shark nets from three NSW beaches on hold after fatal attack

image.altText: Black and dark grey smoke clouds rising above an airport terminal building, seen from an outdoor car park

props.synopsis: Israeli officials say the Houthis launched multiple drones targeting an area near the Ramon International Airport, closing airspace and forcing a halt to flights.

title.children: Yemen's Houthi rebels launch drone attack on Israeli airport

image.altText: Immigration Raid Hyundai Plant

props.synopsis: South Korea's presidential chief of staff Kang Hoon-sik says the country has finalised negotiations with the Trump administration to release more than 300 workers detained in an immigration raid at a Hyundai plant.

title.children: 'Deal reached' to bring home South Koreans detained in US raids

image.altText: Andrew Moore, Billy Moore and Karina Brown in the ABC Sport commentary box before a Women's State of Origin game.

props.synopsis: ABC Sport commentator Andrew Moore says he does not know when he will be back on the radio, but is "oddly excited" about the recovery process after his heart attack last month.

title.children: At the age of 56, ABC commentator Andrew Moore starts afresh after 'miracle survival'

image.altText: an australian navy warship sails next to a philippine navy ship

props.synopsis: China's military says it followed and warned Australian guided-missile destroyer HMAS Brisbane and a Canadian ship as they transited the sensitive waterway.

title.children: 'Causing trouble': China says it followed Australian ship in Taiwan Strait

image.altText: Stephen Crichton of the Bulldogs is tackled by Cameron Munster of the Storm in an NRL game.

props.synopsis: The NRL releases the schedule for the first two weeks of the finals series, with the Storm and Bulldogs starting the playoffs on Friday night.

title.children: NRL reveals finals schedule, including shake-up for semis in week two

image.altText: Man wearing glasses being carried by people in high-vis jackets

props.synopsis: London police arrest about 900 Palestine Action supporters, following a previous arrest of nearly 500 supporters last month.

title.children: UK police arrest 900 banned Palestine Action group supporters in London

image.altText: A house on fire.

props.synopsis: Police say two people in their 60s have life-threatening injuries after being assaulted at a house in Coffs Harbour, with a separate home destroyed by fire.

title.children: Man arrested after couple critically injured in assault, woman escapes house fire

image.altText: A red and black graphic of a crowd in silhouette under a white supremacist flag and the Australian flag.

props.synopsis: As the National Socialist Network follows the script of a far-right playbook in an attempt to position itself as a political movement, there are moves to have it proscribed as a terrorist group.

title.children: How overseas Neo-Nazi groups are shaping Australia's far-right

image.altText: A house auction in Norwood

props.synopsis: The "inflation nutters" in New Zealand adopted inflation targeting first, and Australia pinched their idea. But the policy has unresolved issues, a former RBA deputy governor says.

title.children: The RBA has never known what to do about property prices, former deputy governor says

image.altText: Albanese and Morrison pull the same pose, listening with each of their fingers entwined

props.synopsis: When he lashed Scott Morrison over the multiple ministries affair, Anthony Albanese said his predecessor "operated in darkness". But this week, a PM with a patchy transparency record of his own announced a plan to dim the lights.

title.children: Albanese scoffed at Morrison's secrecy. Then he copied it

image.altText: A portrait of Renee Gracie preparing to race in the 2023 GT World Challenge.

props.synopsis: Renee Gracie had her dream career in motorsport, but says sexism and the culture forced her out. OnlyFans kept her afloat in some dark days, and now she's back on the circuit with their support.

title.children: OnlyFans restored Renee Gracie’s self esteem and her motorsport career

image.altText: Aryna Sabalenka kisses the US Open trophy

props.synopsis: World number one Aryna Sabalenka successfully defends her US Open title, with a straight-sets win in the final against American Amanda Anisimova at Flushing Meadows.

title.children: Sabalenka apologises for 'really terrible' behaviour after claiming US Open win
